alert.headline: NWS Tulsa (Eastern Oklahoma)
alert.desc:
...FLOOD WARNING REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 3 PM CDT THIS AFTERNOON...
* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall continues.
* WHERE...A portion of northeast Oklahoma, including the following
counties, Creek, Mayes, Osage, Pawnee, Rogers, Tulsa and Wagoner.
* WHEN...Until 300 PM CDT.
* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying
and flood-prone locations is imminent or occurring. It will take
several hours for all the water from these storms to work through
local drainage systems in urban areas.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 1145 AM CDT, Doppler radar indicated slow moving
thunderstorms with very heavy rainfall across the warned
area. Between 1 and 4 inches of rain have fallen. Additional
thunderstorms will produce brief heavy rainfall across
already saturated areas through 1 pm.
- Additional rainfall amounts of 0.5 to 1 inch are possible in
the warned area.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Tulsa...                           Broken Arrow...
Sand Springs...                    Claremore...
Bristow...                         Pryor...
Owasso...                          Bixby...
Sapulpa...                         Jenks...
Glenpool...                        Coweta...
Pryor Creek...                     Skiatook...
Catoosa...                         Collinsville...
Verdigris...                       Mannford...
Drumright...
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

alert.headline: Flood Warning issued May 05 at 4:57PM CDT until May 06 at 1:00PM CDT by NWS
alert.note: Alert for Tulsa (Oklahoma) Issued by the National Weather Service
alert.desc:
...FLOOD WARNING IN EFFECT UNTIL 5 PM CDT FRIDAY...
* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall is expected.
* WHERE...Portions of east central Oklahoma, northeast Oklahoma and
southeast Oklahoma, including the following counties, in east
central Oklahoma, Muskogee and Okfuskee. In northeast Oklahoma,
Creek, Mayes, Okmulgee, Rogers, Tulsa and Wagoner. In southeast
Oklahoma, Haskell, McIntosh and Pittsburg.
* WHEN...Until 500 PM CDT Friday.
* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying
and flood-prone locations is imminent or occurring. Numerous roads
remain closed due to flooding. Low-water crossings are inundated
with water and may not be passable. It will take several hours for
all the water from these storms to work through local drainage
systems in urban areas.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 454 PM CDT, The heavy rain has ended. Doppler radar and
automated rain gauges indicated heavy rain due to
thunderstorms. Flooding is already occurring in the warned
area. Widespread rain estimates between 4 and 7 inches of
rain have fallen with 7 to 11 inches estimated in several
locations.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Tulsa...                           Broken Arrow...
Muskogee...                        Okmulgee...
Wagoner...                         Bristow...
Okemah...                          Eufaula...
Bixby...                           Sapulpa...
Jenks...                           Okfuskee...
Glenpool...                        Coweta...
Henryetta...                       Fort Gibson...
Checotah...                        Drumright...
Chouteau...                        Haskell...
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
alert.instruction:
Turn around, don`t drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

alert.headline: Flood Warning issued May 05 at 3:18PM CDT until May 06 at 4:00PM CDT by NWS
alert.note: Alert for Rogers; Tulsa (Oklahoma) Issued by the National Weather Service
alert.desc:
...The Flood Warning is extended for the following rivers in
Oklahoma...
Caney River near Collinsville affecting Tulsa and Rogers Counties.
Arkansas River near Muskogee affecting Muskogee County.
...FLOOD WARNING NOW IN EFFECT FROM THIS EVENING TO TOMORROW
AFTERNOON...
* WHAT...Minor flooding is forecast.
* WHERE...Caney River near Collinsville.
* WHEN...From this evening to tomorrow afternoon.
* IMPACTS...At 27.0 feet, minor agricultural flooding occurs. County
roads north of Collinsville may be covered with water.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 2:30 PM CDT Thursday the stage was 24.0 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to rise above flood stage
this evening to a crest of 26.8 feet just after midnight
tonight. It will then fall below flood stage late tomorrow
morning.
- Flood stage is 26.0 feet.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

alert.headline: Flood Advisory issued May 05 at 1:36PM CDT until May 06 at 1:00PM CDT by NWS
alert.note: Alert for Tulsa (Oklahoma) Issued by the National Weather Service
alert.desc:
...The National Weather Service in Tulsa has issued a Flood Advisory
for the following rivers in Oklahoma...
Bird Creek near Owasso-Mingo affecting Tulsa County.
...FLOOD ADVISORY IN EFFECT FROM THIS AFTERNOON TO EARLY TOMORROW
AFTERNOON...
* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall is expected.
* WHERE...Bird Creek near Owasso-Mingo.
* WHEN...From this afternoon to early tomorrow afternoon.
* IMPACTS...At 17.0 feet, faster flows are expected along the river
but no flooding occurs. Interests near the river and near Mohawk
Park should continue to monitor later forecasts.
At 18.0 feet, minor flooding occurs at Mohawk Park and along 56th
Street North near Mingo Road.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 1:00 PM CDT Thursday the stage was 16.6 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to rise to a crest of 17.6
feet this evening.
- Action stage is 17.0 feet.
- Flood stage is 18.0 feet.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
